{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Constant repairs to the road that links the islands of the Outer Banks has caused some to question the approach in the face of unrelenting erosion.", "abstract": "North Carolina's Outer Banks, home to some of the nation's most celebrated beach communities, offer an extreme example of the difficulty of maintaining houses, roads and other infrastructure in the face of drastic weather events driven in part by a rise in sea level; Outer Banks' barrier islands, facing constant erosion, are repeatedly cut off from the mainland after storms flood the only connecting road, and engineers are hard at work devising a new method of traveling to and from the area.", "section_name": "Science", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Cornelia", "role": "reported", "lastname": "DEAN", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By CORNELIA DEAN", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/06/science/highway-12-outer-banks-lifeline-is-under-siege-by-nature.html", "lead_paragraph": "Constant repairs to the road that links the islands of the Outer Banks has caused some to question the approach in the face of unrelenting erosion.", "headline": {"seo": "Highway 12, Outer Banks Lifeline, Is Under Siege by Nature", "main": "A North Carolina Lifeline Built on Shifting Sands", "print_headline": "A Lifeline Built On Shifting Sands"}, "_id": "51c1e0a97e0d9c0839d29c4e", "word_count": "1715", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2012/03/06/science/06outerbanks-graphic/06outerbanks-graphic-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2012/03/06/science/06outerbanks-graphic/06outerbanks-graphic-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 360, "url": "images/2012/03/06/science/06OUTE_SPAN/06OUTE-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2012/03/06/science/06OUTE_SPAN/06OUTE-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth"